KJV: When Jesus had said this, a woman in the crowd called out to him, ‘How happy is the woman who brought you into the world and fed you!’
Comments:
You changed to “woman [who was in the crowd]”.  What’s the difference between “women [who was in the crowd]” and “woman in the crowd”?

This is similar to your question in 11:43: What's the difference between "places [that are in the synagogues]" and "places in the synagogues".   English freely permits prepositional phrases to modify nouns, as in these two examples, but many languages don't permit these constructions.  Those languages will have to convert these modifying prepositional phrases to relative clauses, and it's pretty complicated for rules to insert the right verb into those relative clause.  I've found that it's much easier if in the semantic representations we convert all modifying PPs to relative clauses, and then the languages that permit PPs to modify nouns (like English) can easily convert these relative clauses to PPs.

Could you put this note in the "Analysis Conventions"?

'each other's(people's) feet' is good.

KJV: God will lift the cover from everything that people want to hide. He will display every secret.
Comments:
"That people have hidden" is literally "that (people)_implicit have covered".  Wasn't sure if your "cover" meanings fit well, so used "have hidden".  []  For second clause, at first had "display" like EE.  There is no theta rule for "display".  In English I would use "reveal" rather than "display".  "Display" is usually used for things you see.  But your word "reveal" seems to have the meaning of helping people understand (like "Jesus revealed that He was the Christ"). Found it easiest to use the literal "God will cause [people to know every thing [that was secret]]."

KJV: The people with authority will accuse you in the synagogues and to rulers. But do not worry about what to say or how you will defend yourself.
Comments:
This verse is difficult.  First, "Synagogue" is in ontology, but not used.  Steve used "temple" (Lk 4:16), which I don't like.  I would prefer "Jewish church" if we're not going to use "synagogue".  Wycliffe Translation Notes uses "court", which gets the essential idea of a trial, but is not very literal.  []  Would like to have "worry" + Proposition ("worry how to show you are innocent") but "worry" doesn't have theta grid for a Proposition.  Switched to just "worry" + "not need to plan".  []  "Bring in" probably implies to accuse.  As you can see from the EE, EE dropped the idea of "bring in" and used "accuse".  My lexicon says for this verse "drag in".  Idea might be "drag into the synagogue to accuse you".  The problem with "accuse" is that it needs a proposition, and then what?  Could say "accuse [that you did a crime]" but what kind of crime?  "Accuse [that you did a crime] [because you are a Christian]"?  Maybe it's best to leave vague like original.  Translation Notes have as an option "arrest you and take you to...".  We have arrest in the ontology but without a theta grid and it's not used.  []  Translation Notes have "you did not do anything wrong" for "are innocent".  You had "innocent" in the ontology.  But could use "that you(disciples) did not do any wrong thing" for "that you(disciples) are innocent".  []  An alternate for the second to last clause is : "You(disciples) do not need [to know [how to show [that you(disciples) are innocent]]]".  But I figured that "plan" carried the "how" meaning implicitly.
--------------------------
I like using 'Jewish church' for 'synagogue.'  Let's make 'synagogue' a complex concept that can be inserted by a rule if the target language has a lexical equivalent - but I'm sure that very few languages that Wycliffe missionaries work in will have 'synagogue'.  Adding another sense of 'worry + propositon' is appropriate here (e.g., John worried about Susan driving in the snow.) so please go ahead and use it.  I also like 'arrest you and take you to ...'  Even though we haven't used 'arrest' yet, it is one of our semantic molecules.  Our semantic molecules are the 3,000 most common words in English according to the Longman Dictionary of Contemporary English.  If you have access to a copy of that, it would be helpful.  They identify the 3,000 most commonly used words and list them in red.  Rather than 'innocent', how about 'did not do bad things'?  'prove' is another semantic molecule, so how about 'you do not need to prove that you did not do bad things'?

KJV: Then Jesus told them this parable. ‘There was a rich man whose land gave him a great harvest.
Comments:
Another possibility is to use "person" for "man" (gender neutral).  Greek has two words for man, and this is the more generic one, anthropos, versus aner.  On the other hand, Greek can have headless NPs that don't have a noun, like in verse 9 "one denying me".  But Gingrich (Greek lexicon) seems to usually encourage a generic meaning for anthropos.  On the other hand, I have the feeling that the Greek would have used "woman" if it was a woman, so it's probably a man.  []  Used "fields" (from Translation Notes) rather than "ground".  There is a unused "land(ground)" word in the ontology that would be more literal and may come in handy later.  But the meaning with "fields" and "land" is pretty much the same I think.
-------------
I think using 'man' is fine.  Yes, we usually use 'field' when talking about places where people grow crops.

KJV: So do not worry about what you will eat and drink.
Comments:
I think this verse needs some work.  Literal is "Do not seek food and drink, and do not worry".  We do have "search for" that we could use for "seek", but I think that "seek" here has more the sense of "fix your attention on".  So the most literal would be something like "Do not fix your attention on getting food and drink.  Don't worry about these things."  Or "Do not devote all your energy on getting food and drink.  Don't worry about these things."  But that seems to be too complex for us to express. [] My revised Easy English above is problematic.  It's not worry about food, but worry about getting food.  Here's what I would prefer if we can do it: "So you(disciples) do not worry (imp) about [how you(disciples) will get your(disciple's) food and drink]" or "So you(disciples) do not worry (imp) about [getting food and drink]".  This better captures the meaning than what I wrote in the Revised EE box (people are worried about getting food rather than about the food itself).  It also has the word "get" which captures some of the meaning of the original "seek".  But for this structure, I think we need a new theta grid for "worry about clause" (now only have "worry about noun".  Or does the relation "about" work here with the "worry" without an argument?  Here's another option from the Tranlation Notes: "You(disciples) do not always be thinking (imp) about [whether you(disciples) will have enough food or drink].  You(disciples) don't worry about these things."  Or here's a slight modification of the first sentence:  "You(disciples) do not always be thinking (imp) about [how you(disciples) will get enough food or drink]".  But for these, it seems we will also need a new theta grid for "think about clause" (or perhaps that's what "consider" is).  Do you have an opinion about these options?
------------------
Back in Luke 12:11 we talked about 'worry' + proposition (e.g., John worried about Susan driving in the snow.).  So I like your final 'Do not worry about how you will get enough food and enough drink.'  Here that rule where English changes 'and' to 'or' because of the negative verb is interesting because the negated verb is in the matrix clause, but the coordinate patients are in the object complement.

'servant' collocates best with 'master'; 'slave' collocates with 'owner.'  We can't start a proposition with 'just-like,' so how about 'You(disciples) (imp) be ready to work just-like ...'  Regarding 'feast', how about 'a feast that is at a wedding', or just '... master that returns to his house from a wedding.'  Yes, 'return' always has a destination, here the implied destination is 'house', so we need to make it explicit.  return-A is 'go back', return-B is 'come back.'  In English we just say 'return', but some languages (e.g., Korean) have different words for 'return-come' and 'return-go'.  Similarly in English we say 'enter' whether the person is 'going in' or 'coming in', but some languages have two different words.  I don't see where 'may' fits in this verse.

KJV: Some servants are awake when their master returns. Those servants are happy. I tell you that the master will get ready. He will make the servants sit down. Then the master will serve them at the table.
Comments:
It's more literally "Those servants whom the master sees are waiting for him when he arrives are happy", but construction of EE is simpler and seems to mean essentially the same thing.  Translation Notes use "If the master returns and sees..., then the servants will be happy."  []  "Are happy" is literally "are blessed".  I'm thinking maybe "happy" is better in this context.  Usually, I reserve "blessed" for blessed by God.  How would you separate uses of "happy" and "blessed"?  Longman seems to define "blessed" as helped and protected by God (4th meaning, probably not a central concept).  I think of "blessed" as meaning having received a vague and unspecified set of good things from God. []  "You(disciples) listen (imp) to the thing [that I(Jesus) tell you]." is literally "Truly I tell you that..."  []  Translation Notes have "The master will tell the servants to sit down AT THE TABLE."  No literal "table", but implied.  []  "Sit down" is literal "recline".  []  Used "tell them to sit down" like Translation Notes.  "Make them sit down" (EE) is better in English, but wanted to avoid impression that this is forceful since it's clear that the master is being nice to his servants.

I'm glad to see that you have Longman's Dictionary.  If you ever wonder whether or not a word should be in TBTA's ontology, if a word is in red in Longman's, then the word definitely belongs in the ontology and you can feel free to use it even if it hasn't yet been used in TBTA.  Also, if a word is in the ontology but not in red in Longman's, then we need to tag that word in the ontology as complex, and then come up with a simple way of expressing that concept using Longman's defining vocabulary.  Regarding 'happy' vs 'blessed', I agree with you.  I see 'happy' as an internal emotion, and 'blessed' as something God does to/for us.  Soon I'll go through the ontology and check each entry with Longman's.

KJV: Then the master will come back one day when the servant does not expect him. He will give the servant a severe punishment. The servant will have the same fate as those servants who were not loyal.
Comments:
Translation Notes, Gingrich lexicon, and Morris's Luke commentary have "severely/greatly punish".  More literal is "The master will cut the servant into pieces," which I like better, but I hesitate to go against all these authorities. The following clause is literally "the master will place the part/portion of him with the unbelievers".  This might mean  "The master will put parts of the servant's body in the place [where the bodies of the people [who do not have faith] are put]".  I'm imagining that this means Gehenna (if I remember the name correctly), the place outside Jerusalem where unclean things were thrown.  KJV and EE have for this clause the idea of "fate" (EE) or "portion" (KJV).  NIV has "assign him a place with the unbelievers", which is similar to my translation in the "Revised Easy English Text" box. The Translation Notes have "will put him in a place with others who are unfaithful".  Used most literal "people who are not believers", but don't want "believers" to be literally Christians (if that is what it means) as in gloss of "believer". Another option would be "people who do not have faith".  Translation Notes have "people who are unfaithful", but I think "people who do not have faith" captures "unbelievers" meaning better.  What do you like for this verse?  When we settle this, we can move some of this discussion to the "Analysis Notes" section.  []  "On a day [when...]" is literal.  OK would be just "[when...]".  []  For last clause, used "a place [where the people [who..." instead of "with the people [who...".  You said relative clauses are better than prepositional phrases, right?  
-------------------
So does the master kill the servant?  If so, I think we should say that.  The NIV has 'cut him to pieces' like you said, so there's a pretty good authority supporting that view.  The relative clause 'people who are not believers' seems strange to me here, even when I read it in the NIV.  When I read it, I thought 'non-Christians'.  I don't know if that's what Jesus meant.  Do you think He meant non-Christians?  Yes, a relative clause in this situation is better than a PP.

KJV: But another servant may not know what his master wants. That servant may do something wrong that deserves punishment. But the master will hit him with only a few blows. God requires much from the person to whom he gives much. He will expect much more from the person to whom he has given more’.
Comments:
I have "does some bad things".  Literal is "things deserving of stripes".  Could do "things that are worthy of punishment" if "worthy" can have that sense.  []  Or "hit this servant with few blows" for "punish this servant little".  Again, it's literally "slave".  []  For the last two clauses, I have the text you suggested.  Original is "From everyone to whom much is given, much will be demanded from him, and from everyone to whom much was deposited, exceedingly more they will ask from him."  There are some issues here.  If I use "person" for the original giver (left vague in the original), does "person" include God?  Seems not since the gloss is "human being".  So it seemed that I needed to choose "person" or "God".  Went with "God" like Translation Notes (though "they" in original seems to be begging us to leave it vague).  Second problem is that, as we discussed in our emails, "much" and "more" are in the originals without a head noun and it seems that the original meaning fits better with an uncountable "thing".  Another possibility is to get very interpretive.  Translation Notes has something like "If God gives you blessings and allows you to accomplish much, you should be responsible to Him.  When God has entrusted much responsibility to someone, He will require more from you than from one who has been entrusted with less responsibility."  But that sounds complicated to express.
------------
I think 'does bad things' is fine.  To parallel the previous verse, how about 'hit the servant a few times'?  I agree, the TN is complicated.  I think it's good to expicitly use 'God' rather than 'person'.  I know Jesus left it implicit, probably so that this sentence fits with both the master/servant situation in the parable and the God/person situation that Jesus is really talking about, but we need to make it explicit, and I think using 'God' rather than 'person' is the best option.

KJV: If someone accuses you, you should try hard to be at peace with him. Do this while you are on the way to the court. If you do not, he will drag you to the judge. The judge will order the police to put you in prison.
Comments:
Literal is "And as you are going with your adversary/opponent/accuser before/to the magnistrate/ruler in the way, try to make a deal/settle/make an agreement".  Some other possibilities for "try to make peace": "try to have peace" or "try to agree", or "you(person) should try [to agree about the things [that you(person) will do [to have/make peace]]]" or "you(person) should try [to agree about the things [that you(person) will do [to satisfy the person]]]" or "you(person) should try [to agree about the things [that you(person) will do [to make the person happy]]]".  "Satisfy" is a good word for this situation and is in the ontology but not used.
-----------------
I don't really like 'make peace with the person.'  Also, is there a ruler, judge, and guard involved, or just a judge and guard?  In the NIV, does 'magistrate' refer to someone other than the judge, or is that another term for the judge?  'satisfy' is in Longman's as a semantic molecule, so we're free to use it.  Here's my suggestion (I'll assume for now that the magistrate and the judge are different people, but I'm not certain of that): 'If a person accuses you of doing bad things, you should try to satisfy that person.  And you should try to talk to that person.  You (imp) talk to that person while you are walking to the ruler.  If the ruler agrees with the person that says you did bad things, the ruler will send you to the judge.  Then the judge will send you to the guard.  And the guard will put you in prison.'  Since you have a Longman's Dictionary, if a word in the ontology isn't used but is in red in Longman's, please feel free to use that word.

Notes: "Noble" is a level 4 word that can be expanded as "person [who is in a powerful family]". [] This parable may allude to Herod the Great or Archelaus, who traveled to Rome to be made king by the Emperor.  Historical note from Wikipedia, "Josephus describes Jews sending an embassy to Augustus, while Archelaus is travelling to Rome, to complain that they do not want Archelaus as their ruler; when Archelaus returns, he arranged for 3000 of his enemies to be brought to him at the Temple in Jerusalem, where he had them slaughtered." "By the emperor" is an implicit passive agent which can be deleted if the language allows.
KJV: He said, ‘There was once a prince, who was going to a distant country to receive royal power. Then he planned to return home.
Comments: R: Regarding "noble", lord" is the LDD word that means "a person who has a rank in the aristocracy (people with land, money, and power), especially in England".  The literal Greek text is "well born", meaning of noble birth.  Note that the words for "Lord" (capitalized) that we now have in the ontology are our specialized meanings, one meaning God and the other meaning Jesus. The LDD word "lord" may stress the meaning of "rank" referring to an official title.  As we discussed, will use a level 4 word "noble", which can be expanded as "person [who is in a powerful family]". [] The literal here is "to receive a kingship", i.e., rule.  My Greek handbook has for the word "kingdom" here, "kingship, sovereignty ", which is exactly what I suggested we consider "kingdom" to mean, so we could use the word "kingdom" here.  "To be given the kingdom of the Lord's country by the emperor".  [] "By the emperor" is an implicit passive agent.  Or "by a person".  It's not explicit in the original.  Here I'm assuming that the listeners think of someone like Herod making a trip to Rome to be given the rule of Israel.

"Peace" is here in Greek and English probably two things, "lack of war" and "right relationship with God", and both are probably intended in this verse. "Relationship" is in the LDD, and we could expand this as something like "peace(lack of war) and a good relationship with God".  []  More literal would be "But these things were hidden from you".  But "hidden" is abstract here and also we would need an implicit passive agent, so I prefer what I wrote above. [] Or "do not KNOW these things".

KJV: But when the tenants saw him, they said to one another, “This is the son. Let us kill him. We shall get what he should have received after his father’s death”.
Comments: R: Or "thing [that the farmers WOULD do]". I might not want to write it with "should" in English because of the association of "should" with something that it is good for us to do. But one person's idea of "should" is not necessarily the same as another's. []  Here again is a case where it says literally that THEY said "This son will...", but if I write it like that, it seems to mean that they are all speaking in unison.  The literal text (which sounds good also in English) is "Having seen the son, the farmers debated among themselves, saying "This is the heir. Let us kill him, in order that we may obtain the inheritance."  Here are the two possibilities I have considered for this text: We could assume that there was one main speaker, and write it like this: "One farmer said to the other farmers, '[This son will get the garden [when the person [that owns this garden] dies]]. We(farmers) should kill this son [so that we(farmers) will be able [to keep this garden]].'  And the other farmers agreed with the farmer [who spoke]."  Here's the other possibility that does not use a direct quote, and that I have used above: "But [after these farmers saw this son] these farmers talked with each other about the thing [that these farmers should do]. These farmers realized [that this son would get the garden [when the person [who owned the garden] died]]]. But these farmers thought [that these farmers would be able [to keep the garden] [if this son died]]. So these farmers decided [to kill this son]." Which do you like best?  One of them keeps the literal quote, but has to make an arbitrary decision about who speaks, when probably one person said one thing and another said another. The other option avoids this issue by writing it in terms of the thoughts of the group.  Another option would be to have a new sense of "say" or "discuss" that summarizes a group discussion as a quote (the literal way it's written).

Comments: R: Would like the structure (note curly braces) "{the thing [that is from the Scriptures] } [that I(Jesus) will tell to you(people)]". []  "Scriptures" is in the ontology but not in the LDD. A possible explication is "God's book". [] Or "decided [not to use this stone]", but I think that the text that I used has more flair. ***Or change "useless" to "not useful"? "Useless" is in the LDD, but not currently in the ontology.  I'm guessing you will say we should change this.*** Or "The people [that were building a building] did not want this stone" (in Translation Notes).   [] Leon Morris's commentary on Luke says that "it is not certain where the 'head of the corner stone' was... Either way it is of great importance". Considering this, the above translation (like EE) seems appropriate.
